04638nam a22005775i 9780822390923DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223909237 a10.1515/97808223909232doi  a(DE-B1597)554281  a(OCoLC)456471254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJK2316b.D43 2009 7aPOL0100002bisacsh  aCC 78002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17691:1 aDean, Jodi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy and Other Neoliberal Fantasies :bCommunicative Capitalism and Left Politics /cJodi Dean. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION Post-Politics and Left Victory -- t1 Technology the promises of communicative capitalism -- t2 Free Trade the neoliberal fantasy -- t3 Democracy a knot of hope and despair -- t4 Resolve speaking of evil -- t5 Ethics left responsiveness and retreat -- t6 Certainty 9 / 11 conspiracy theories and psychosis -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDemocracy and Other Neoliberal Fantasies is an impassioned call for the realization of a progressive left politics in the United States. Through an assessment of the ideologies underlying contemporary political culture, Jodi Dean takes the left to task for its capitulations to conservatives and its failure to take responsibility for the extensive neoliberalization implemented during the Clinton presidency. She argues that the left's ability to develop and defend a collective vision of equality and solidarity has been undermined by the ascendance of "communicative capitalism," a constellation of consumerism, the privileging of the self over group interests, and the embrace of the language of victimization. As Dean explains, communicative capitalism is enabled and exacerbated by the Web and other networked communications media, which reduce political energies to the registration of opinion and the transmission of feelings. The result is a psychotic politics where certainty displaces credibility and the circulation of intense feeling trumps the exchange of reason.Dean's critique ranges from her argument that the term democracy has become a meaningless cipher invoked by the left and right alike to an analysis of the fantasy of free trade underlying neoliberalism, and from an examination of new theories of sovereignty advanced by politicians and left academics to a look at the changing meanings of "evil" in the speeches of U.S. presidents since the mid-twentieth century. She emphasizes the futility of a politics enacted by individuals determined not to offend anyone, and she examines questions of truth, knowledge, and power in relation to 9/11 conspiracy theories. Dean insists that any reestablishment of a vital and purposeful left politics will require shedding the mantle of victimization, confronting the marriage of neoliberalism and democracy, and mobilizing different terms to represent political strategies and goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismzUnited States. 0aPolitical partieszUnited States. 0aPolitics, PracticalzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390923zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390923423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390923.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d